// ============================================================================
// VidyaSetu — Revised Database Schema (PostgreSQL / Prisma)
// ============================================================================
//
// WHAT CHANGED FROM THE ORIGINAL SCHEMA, AND WHY:
//
// 1. Every table is scoped by schoolId (multi-tenant isolation). Composite
//    unique constraints (e.g. admission number, receipt number) are unique
//    PER SCHOOL, not globally — two different schools on the same platform
//    can both have a "Roll No. 1" or "Receipt #001".
//
// 2. Added AcademicYear as a first-class table. The original schema put a
//    single classId directly on Student — that overwrites history every
//    time a student is promoted, so you lose last year's class/roll/section
//    the moment you promote them. Now: Class rows belong to an AcademicYear,
//    and Enrollment is a join table (Student x Class x AcademicYear). A
//    student promoted from 5-A to 6-B gets a NEW Enrollment row; the old one
//    stays untouched. This also lets you generate historical report cards,
//    attendance %, and fee ledgers for any past year.
//
// 3. Money fields use Decimal(10,2), never Float. Floats introduce rounding
//    errors in financial data — this matters for fee receipts, salary
//    slips, and refunds, all of which get audited.
//
// 4. Loose strings ("status", "role", "paymentMode" as free text) are now
//    enums. This is a data-integrity issue in the original schema: nothing
//    stopped someone from inserting "teecher" or "Present " (trailing
//    space) and silently breaking every report that filters on that column.
//
// 5. The original User table tried to hold every role's fields on one row
//    (bloodGroup and medicalConditions live on Student already, which is
//    good — but Teacher, Parent, and generic Staff were left undifferen-
//    tiated). Here, User is pure identity/auth, and each role gets its own
//    1:1 profile table. A Clerk row is never left with 40 nullable columns
//    meant for Students.
//
// 6. Sensitive data is split into its own tables with narrower access
//    scope than the parent record: StudentHealthRecord, InfirmaryVisit,
//    and GrievanceReport are NOT part of StudentProfile. This lets you
//    grant a Teacher read access to StudentProfile without also handing
//    them medical history or POCSO complaint records — see the RBAC
//    matrix in the accompanying report.
//
// 7. Nothing that has academic, financial, or legal evidentiary value is
//    ever hard-deleted. Sensitive/record-of-truth tables carry deletedAt
//    for soft delete; AuditLog, GrievanceReport, and Marks are intentionally
//    append-only at the application layer (no update/delete endpoints).
//
// 8. Added tables the original schema was missing entirely: admissions/
//    enquiry pipeline, exam scheduling, homework submission, library,
//    hostel, health & vaccination records, certificates, visitor/gate
//    management, POCSO grievance handling, alumni, and — because this
//    platform processes children's personal data in India — DPDP Act
//    consent records, data-subject-request tracking, and breach logging.
//
// 9. OTP is stored as a hash, never plaintext, with an attempt counter.
//    RfidScan and BusLocation are treated as high-volume, short-retention
//    logs (see DataRetentionPolicy) rather than data you keep forever —
//    raw GPS pings and gate-scan logs are exactly the kind of data the
//    DPDP Act's "data minimisation" principle expects you to prune.
//
// A NOTE ON "LOGICAL" FOREIGN KEYS:
// Fields like approvedByUserId, recordedByUserId, issuedByUserId, etc. are
// foreign keys to User.id. To keep this file readable, only the high-
// traffic relations (identity, enrollment, attendance, fees) are modelled
// as full Prisma relations with back-reference arrays. The rest are left
// as plain scalar columns with a `-> User.id` comment. Add a raw SQL
// FOREIGN KEY constraint for these in your migration regardless — referen-
// tial integrity at the database level does not depend on whether Prisma
// models the relation object, and it should not be optional for columns
// that gate approvals, payments, or medical sign-off.
//
// ============================================================================

datasource db {
  provider = "postgresql"
  url      = env("DATABASE_URL")
}

generator client {
  provider = "prisma-client-js"
}

